<article>
    <h1>ROAST CHICKEN AND CHOPPED TUR&#xAD;KEY</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201213/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-13"><time>2020-12-13</time></a>
        - <span>FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Mind­ful of smaller group din­ing this year, Per­anakan restau­rant The Blue Gin­ger has in­tro­duced an ayam pang­gang roast chicken dish ($38) – which uses a corn-fed French chicken – that can feed up to five peo­ple. Add the aro­matic new ox­tail ren­dang ($48), which comes in three size­able pieces.</p>
    <p>At ca­sual restau­rant chain Delifrance, its Splen­dor Chicken Spread ($128, for three to five peo­ple) bun­dle in­cludes cit­rus herb roast chicken, potato gratin and a Mango Pas­sion log cake.</p>
    <p>Oth­ers have found cre­ative ways to show­case tur­key in a more man­age­able por­tion. Crowne Plaza Changi Air­port’s salted egg yolk tur­key roulade ($98+) is a con­ve­nient al­ter­na­tive to the full-sized 6kg salted egg yolk roast tur­key ($168+).</p>
    <p>Both op­tions come with XO crab meat fried rice, sea­sonal greens and salted egg yolk cream sauce.</p>
    <p>Baba Chews Bar & Eatery at Ho­tel In­digo Sin­ga­pore Ka­tong of­fers laksa tur­key pie ($59) and tur­key ngoh hi­ang “golden pil­low” ($75) – a spin on ngoh hi­ang stuffed with tur­key and wrapped in bean­curd skin.</p>
    <p>No need to worry about carv­ing Good­wood Park Ho­tel’s new “har cheong” tur­key ($118 nett), as the prawn-paste tur­key dish comes chopped up into about eight pieces, and is served with rice and dips.</p>
    <p>Tur­key is also fea­tured in the mini tur­key shep­herd’s pie with duo potato and cheese crum­ble ($38 nett); shred­ded tur­key with leek in se­same pock­ets ($38 nett); and crispy “char siew” tur­key with pine nuts kataifi ($38 nett), in­spired by bar­be­cued pork pas­try (char siew sou). A spokesman for Good­wood Park Ho­tel says: “We kept in mind that home cel­e­bra­tions are likely to be on a smaller scale and that guests may pre­fer dishes with in­di­vid­ual serv­ings.”</p>

